The bug is clear from the source and sanitizer output.

ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:23` — in `load_blob`, when the recoverable parse error path is taken (name length > 4), `b->name` is freed at line 23 but `b` is still returned to the caller with `b->name` now a dangling pointer. Later, `destroy_blob` at line 33 calls `free(b->name)` again on that already-freed pointer, causing a double-free.

LOCAL FIX: After freeing `b->name` on the error path, set the pointer to NULL so `destroy_blob`'s `free(b->name)` becomes a safe no-op:
```c
free(b->name);
b->name = NULL;   /* prevent double-free in destroy_blob */
b->size = 0;
return b;
```

GLOBAL FIX: Establish an ownership invariant: every pointer field in a struct must either be valid or NULL at all times, and every cleanup function must null out fields after freeing them (`free(b->name); b->name = NULL;` inside `destroy_blob` too). Additionally, adopt a "single-exit" pattern for constructors — rather than partially initializing a struct and returning it in a degraded state, either return a fully valid object or return NULL (and free all intermediate state internally). Callers then only ever see fully-owned or absent objects, eliminating the ambiguous "blob with freed internals" state entirely.
